Ebola virus emerged in West Africa in December 2013. The high population mobility and
poor public health infrastructure in this region led to the development of the largest Ebola
On September 26, 2014, China dispatched a Mobile Biosafety Level-3 Laboratory (MBSL-3
Lab) and a well-trained diagnostic teamto Sierra Leone to assist in EVDdiagnosis using
quantitative real-time PCR, which allowed the diagnosis of suspected EVDcases in less than
4 hours fromthe time of sample receiving. This laboratory was composed of three container
vehicles equipped with advanced ventilation system, communication system, electricity and
gas supply system. We strictly applied multiple safety precautions to reduce exposure risks.
Personnel, materials, water and air flowmanagement were the key elements of the biosafety
measures in the MBSL-3 Lab. Air samples were regularly collected fromthe MBSL-3 Lab,
but no evidence of Ebola virus infectious aerosols was detected. Potentially contaminated
objects were also tested by collecting swabs. On one occasion, a pipette tested positive for
EVD. A total of 1,635 suspected EVDcases (824 positive [50.4%]) were tested fromSeptem-
ber 28 to November 11, 2014, and no member of the diagnostic teamwas infected with
Ebola virus or other pathogens, including Lassa fever. The specimens tested included blood
(69.2%) and oral swabs (30.8%) with positivity rates of 54.2%and 41.9%, respectively. The
